cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.CL, cs.CC, cs.CY 

This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it discusses the development of computational models for human-like intelligence. It may also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as the paper applies collaborative filtering recommenders to investigate the effects of inconsistencies and noise in data. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of data-driven methods in a field of research concerned with gaining high-level theoretical insight, which could place it in the sub-categories of cs.CL (Computation and Language) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper may also belong to cs.CY (Computers and Society) as it discusses the implications of understanding human reasoning for the development of systems that closely interact with humans.
